They often are, and there’s a good cognitive reason for that.

Maps take advantage of how the brain naturally organizes information:

* Spatial memory is powerful. Humans evolved to remember where food, shelter, and danger were. We tend to remember locations more easily than arbitrary lists.
* Relationships become visible. Instead of memorizing isolated facts, you see how things connect—north/south, close/far, branching paths, clusters.
* They create landmarks. Just as you remember “the coffee shop on the corner,” you remember ideas by where they sit in the map.
* Exploration is rewarding. A map invites curiosity. You can zoom in, zoom out, and discover new routes instead of reading linearly.
* Multiple retrieval paths. If you forget one detail, you can often reconstruct it from neighboring landmarks.

This aligns with one of the strongest principles in learning: knowledge organized as a landscape is easier to navigate than knowledge stored as a list.

For your Pantheon project, this suggests something interesting. Rather than presenting doctrines as a long document, imagine a living semantic atlas:

* Continents = major domains (Memory, Intelligence, Communication, Agency)
* Countries = doctrines
* Cities = daemons/operators
* Roads = relationships
* Rivers = information flow
* Mountains = constraints
* Hidden caves = easter eggs and deeper insights
* Portals = cross-domain analogies

People wouldn’t just read Pantheon—they’d explore it. Every visit could reveal another path, giving the feeling of wandering through a world rather than studying a manual. That sense of discovery can make ideas much more memorable while also restoring some of the whimsy and curiosity you’ve emphasized.